27/06/2007
SKOPJE, Macedonia -- Leaders of the ruling coalition and opposition parties met on Tuesday (June 26th) to discuss the draft law on the public prosecutor's office and election of a public prosecutor. 
Prime Minister Nikola Gruevski told reporters the talks are moving in the right direction, adding the government accepted four of the opposition's six requirements.
In other news Tuesday, a Skopje court handed down prison sentences to five former border police officials convicted of bribery. 
They reportedly accepted 10 euros per passenger for failing to perform a detailed check of passports. 
The arrests were part of large-scale operation conducted by the Interior Ministry recently. 
(MIA, Makfax, MRT - 26/06/07)
